), 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. clypealis" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="clypealis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. clypealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Medvedev) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Habitus of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. and P. clypealis. A P. boreri sp. nov., male, dorsal view B Same, ventral view C P. boreri, female, dorsal view D P. clypealis, male, dorsal view E Same, ventral view F P. clypealis, female, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380663" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">8D-F</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hsingtzungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="hsingtzungi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. hsingtzungi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Habitus of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., male, dorsal view B P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., female, dorsal view C Same, ventral view D P. smaragdina, male, dorsal view E P. smaragdina, female, dorsal view F Same, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380670" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">15A-C</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. smaragdina" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="smaragdina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. smaragdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gressitt and Kimoto) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Habitus of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., male, dorsal view B P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., female, dorsal view C Same, ventral view D P. smaragdina, male, dorsal view E P. smaragdina, female, dorsal view F Same, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380670" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">15D-F</figureCitation>
), are characterized by their golden green coloration. They can be identified based on their distribution: 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. boreri" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="boreri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. boreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. from India, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. clypealis" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="clypealis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. clypealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Vietnam, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hsingtzungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="hsingtzungi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. hsingtzungi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. from Laos, and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. smaragdina" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="smaragdina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. smaragdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from China. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Bezdek, 2020" authorityName="Lee &amp; Bezděk" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pseudotheopea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudotheopea boreri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boreri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Pseudotheopea boreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Habitus of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. and P. clypealis. A P. boreri sp. nov., male, dorsal view B Same, ventral view C P. boreri, female, dorsal view D P. clypealis, male, dorsal view E Same, ventral view F P. clypealis, female, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380663" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">8A</figureCitation>
) is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hsingtzungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="hsingtzungi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. hsingtzungi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Habitus of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., male, dorsal view B P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., female, dorsal view C Same, ventral view D P. smaragdina, male, dorsal view E P. smaragdina, female, dorsal view F Same, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380670" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">15A</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. smaragdina" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="smaragdina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. smaragdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Habitus of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., male, dorsal view B P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., female, dorsal view C Same, ventral view D P. smaragdina, male, dorsal view E P. smaragdina, female, dorsal view F Same, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380670" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">15D</figureCitation>
) by sharing the indistinct longitudinal ridges on the elytra (convex and distinct longitudinal ridges on the elytra in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. clypealis" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="clypealis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. clypealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Habitus of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. and P. clypealis. A P. boreri sp. nov., male, dorsal view B Same, ventral view C P. boreri, female, dorsal view D P. clypealis, male, dorsal view E Same, ventral view F P. clypealis, female, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380663" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">8D</figureCitation>
)), but differs by the presence of convex area surrounding scutellum and with reduced longitudinal ridges on the elytra in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Habitus of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. and P. clypealis. A P. boreri sp. nov., male, dorsal view B Same, ventral view C P. boreri, female, dorsal view D P. clypealis, male, dorsal view E Same, ventral view F P. clypealis, female, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380663" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">8A</figureCitation>
) (without convex area surrounding scutellum on the elytra in those of others (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Habitus of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. and P. clypealis. A P. boreri sp. nov., male, dorsal view B Same, ventral view C P. boreri, female, dorsal view D P. clypealis, male, dorsal view E Same, ventral view F P. clypealis, female, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380663" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">8D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Habitus of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., male, dorsal view B P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., female, dorsal view C Same, ventral view D P. smaragdina, male, dorsal view E P. smaragdina, female, dorsal view F Same, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380670" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">15A, D</figureCitation>
)) and concavity wide between eyes and without erect processes in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Heads of males of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. and P. clypealis. A P. boreri sp. nov., dorsofrontal view B Same, front view C P. clypealis, dorsofrontal view D Same, front view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380664" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">9A, B</figureCitation>
) (concavity wide between eyes with one erect process in those of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. smaragdina" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="smaragdina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. smaragdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Heads of males of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., dorsofrontal view B Same, front view C P. smaragdina, dorsofrontal view D Same, front view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380671" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">16C, D</figureCitation>
); concavity narrowed between eyes and without erect processes in those of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hsingtzungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="hsingtzungi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. hsingtzungi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Heads of males of Pseudotheopea hsingtzungi sp. nov. and P. smaragdina. A P. hsingtzungi sp. nov., dorsofrontal view B Same, front view C P. smaragdina, dorsofrontal view D Same, front view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380671" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">16A, B</figureCitation>
)). In males, the internal aedeagal sac of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. boreri" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="boreri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. boreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. lacks additional sclerites except the median elongate sclerite (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Diagnostic characters of Pseudotheopea boreri sp. nov. A Antenna, male B Antenna, female C Aedeagus, dorsal view D Aedeagus, lateral view E Aedeagus, ventral view F Abdominal ventrite VIII G Gonocoxae H Spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380665" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">10C, D</figureCitation>
). This structure is shared with males of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. gressitti" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="gressitti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. gressitti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Diagnostic characters of Pseudotheopea gressitti sp. nov. A Antenna, male B Antenna, female C Aedeagus, dorsal view D Aedeagus, lateral view E Aedeagus, ventral view F Abdominal ventrite VIII G Gonocoxae H Spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380669" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">14C, D</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. costata" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="costata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. costata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Allard), 
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Bezdek, 2020" authorityName="Lee &amp; Bezděk" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pseudotheopea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudotheopea boreri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boreri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">Pseudotheopea boreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. males differ from both species in possessing a dorso-ventrally flattened aedeagus with a sclerotized ventral surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Diagnostic characters of Pseudotheopea aeneipennis. A Antenna, male B Antenna, female C Aedeagus, dorsal view D Aedeagus, lateral view E Aedeagus, ventral view F Abdominal ventrite VIII G Gonocoxae H Spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380662" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">7C-E</figureCitation>
) (wide aedeagus with membranous ventral surface in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. gressitti" pageId="0" pageNumber="65" rank="species" species="gressitti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">P. gressitti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Diagnostic characters of Pseudotheopea gressitti sp. nov. A Antenna, male B Antenna, female C Aedeagus, dorsal view D Aedeagus, lateral view E Aedeagus, ventral view F Abdominal ventrite VIII G Gonocoxae H Spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.912.47719.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/380669" pageId="0" pageNumber="65">14C-E</figureCitation>
)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
